Norwegians enjoy wine because they value its taste, not because they desire to create a national identity that is dependent on it. While this wine culture shows the nation has matured, it lacks the strength of its predecessors.

Norway has not historically exported wine. Libations, mussel salad, and fermented herring have very little to no connection with wine. It might be that this relationship will never form.

But the mere act of opening a bottle of wine in Norway is a celebration of how far a country has come in its autonomy as a sovereign nation. Norway knows it might never be a fine wine-making nation like France or Italy or Australia.

But it can be a fine wine-drinking nation that continues to inspire Germans and Japanese and Swiss to find reflections in its history and its landscape and in its relationships.

In the end, the wine industry of Norway might see no more than a trickle of its elder wine brother, and it might just see the extinction of its cheap wine brothers.

But it knows wine has no boundaries. It has no religion, no race, no nationality. Instead, it moves freely and evenly mixes with those rooting for Laurence Wine Drinking Nation.
